Ignore poly groups for now, not sure how we should implement these. Flag if more than one ethnicity is present in the relationship?

married <- data_2010 %>% group_by(SERIAL) %>%
  mutate(POLY = any(POLYMAL == "More than one wife linked via SPLOC")) %>%
  filter(POLY == FALSE)

cat("Ratio of poly to married count:", nrow(poly)/nrow(married))
## Ratio of poly to married count: 0.03217694
married <- married %>%
  filter(MARST == "Married/in union") %>%
  mutate(SPLOC = case_when(
    as.factor(SPLOC) == 0 ~ "Spouse not in household",
    .default = as.factor(SPLOC)
  )
)

Handling some unusual cases – the RELATE variable has some entry errors it seems

NOTE: I manually looked through these households – they are all women and many young men. Only one man has the SPLOC filled out, but all other marriage variables indicate marriage. I suspect they calculated age of first marriage using the RELATE variable, creating a chain of error, but could be wrong. I’ll keep them in the data for now

Join the married couples together

NOTE: All M-M pairings were removed, presumably in the erasure of poly groupings

married_joined <- married %>% filter(SEX == "Male") %>%
  inner_join(married %>% mutate(PERNUM = as.character(PERNUM)),
             by = c("SERIAL" = "SERIAL", "SPLOC" = "PERNUM"),
             suffix = c("_M", "_F")
             )
all(married_joined$PERNUM == married_joined$SPLOC_F) # Ensuring everyone is correctly paired
## [1] TRUE
all(married_joined$SEX_F != married_joined$SEX_M) # Verify opposite-sex
## [1] TRUE

See how many households have more than one pairing

## Ratio of households with more than one pairing to all households: 0.01075269

Add the variables of interest

married_joined <- married_joined %>% mutate(
  INTERMAR = case_when(
    ETHNICZM_M != ETHNICZM_F ~ "Yes",
    ETHNICZM_M == ETHNICZM_F ~ "No",
    .default = "Something went wrong"),
  YRMAR = 2010 - (as.numeric(AGE_F) - as.numeric(AGEMARR_F)),
  URBAN = ifelse(POPDENSGEO2_M > 20, "URBAN", "RURAL"),
  FULL_RESIDE = (as.numeric(AGE_F) - as.numeric(AGEMARR_F)) <= MIGYRS1_F)

Subsetting data

by_province <- married_joined %>%
  group_by(PROVINCE_M, INTERMAR) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'PROVINCE_M'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
by_district <- married_joined %>%
  group_by(DISTRICT_M, INTERMAR) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'DISTRICT_M'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
by_year <- married_joined %>%
  group_by(YRMAR, INTERMAR) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'YRMAR'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
by_year_block <- married_joined %>%
  mutate(YEAR_BLOCK = cut(YRMAR, breaks = seq(1941, 2011, by = 5),
                          right = FALSE,
                          labels = paste(seq(1941, 2006, by = 5),
                                         seq(1945, 2010, by = 5), sep = "-"))) %>%
  group_by(YEAR_BLOCK, INTERMAR) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'YEAR_BLOCK'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
by_year_block_urban <- married_joined %>%
  mutate(YEAR_BLOCK = cut(YRMAR, breaks = seq(1941, 2011, by = 5),
                          right = FALSE,
                          labels = paste(seq(1941, 2006, by = 5),
                                         seq(1945, 2010, by = 5), sep = "-"))) %>%
  group_by(YEAR_BLOCK, INTERMAR, URBAN) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'YEAR_BLOCK', 'INTERMAR'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
by_year_block_urban_subset <- married_joined %>%
  filter(FULL_RESIDE) %>%
  mutate(YEAR_BLOCK = cut(YRMAR, breaks = seq(1941, 2011, by = 5),
                          right = FALSE,
                          labels = paste(seq(1941, 2006, by = 5),
                                         seq(1945, 2010, by = 5), sep = "-"))) %>%
  group_by(YEAR_BLOCK, INTERMAR, URBAN) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(relative_frequency = count / sum(count)) %>%
  filter(INTERMAR == "Yes") %>% 
  ungroup()

combo_counts <- as.data.frame(table(married_joined$ETHNICZM_M, married_joined$ETHNICZM_F))
colnames(combo_counts) <- c("ethnicity_m", "ethnicity_f", "count")
combo_counts <- combo_counts %>% filter(ethnicity_m != ethnicity_f)

ggplot(combo_counts, aes(x = ethnicity_m, y = ethnicity_f)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = log(count+1)), color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "blue") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Intermarriage Combinations Logged",
       x = "ETHNICITY_M",
       y = "ETHNICITY_F",
       fill = "Count") +
  theme_pubr() +
